The code to perform all calculations and their result is also provided below. Once you have run this code your self, then you will have to repeat all step on your own using a different dataset.

STEP 2

Build a Frequency Distribution Table

First we need to determine the width of the class intervals. Then estimate the frequency of cases on each of those interval and lastly calculate the relative frequency. Unless we have a good reason to want to use asymmetric size classes or specific ones, we can use the R function hist to get this information.

################ BUILDING A FREQUENCY DISTRIBUTION TABLE ###########

#1 We first generate the class intervals or breaks
    ##1.2 estimate the range of values of the size_cm
max(hhsize$size_cm)-min(hhsize$size_cm)
    ##1.3 decide the number of classes. 
    ## tell r to create a vector named "binNum" by creating a sequence from 0 to 36 every 4 numbers
binNum <-seq(0,36,by=4)
View(binNum)

#2 Then we generate the size classes by converting 
## the hedgehog values to a factor, using the intervals or breaks  as cut points
sizeClass<-cut(hhsize$size_cm,binNum)

##3 we use the table function to count the frequencies for each class
## that is, how many values are in the size class interval or bin
## and use transform to get a vertical layout. 

freq_table<-transform(table(sizeClass)) 
View(freq_table)                          

## PRACTICE: try this command without the transform function and inspect its class()
## Remember to also delete the set of parentheses corresponding to
## that function

#4 lastly, we create a data frame for our frequency distribution table by adding:
## (1) the relative frequency using the prop.table function  and (2) the cumulative frequency using ## the cumsum function (search the help to learn what exactly each of  these functions do)

groupFrequency<-transform(freq_table,Rel_freq=prop.table(Freq),Cum_Freq=cumsum(Freq))

View(groupFrequency)

Copy and paste the table into your Word Answer file.

Assuming the dataset of sizes is a representative sample of the population of hedgehogs in easthampton, answer:

Question 2: What proportion of hedgehogs in that county would be able to pass through fence holes that are 16 cm in diameter?

Now we are going to build a second frequency table, but this time we will use a different width for the bins to reduce the number of class intervals.

## tell r to create a vector named "binNum2" by creating a sequence from 0 to 36 every 9 numbers
binNum2 <-seq(0,36,by=9)
View(binNum)

#2 Then we generate the size classes by converting 
## the hedgehog values to a factor, using the intervals or breaks  as cut points
sizeClass2<-cut(hhsize$size_cm,binNum2)

##3 we use the table function to count the frequencies for each class
## that is, how many values are in the size class interval or bin
## and use transform to get a vertical layout. 

freq_table2<-transform(table(sizeClass2)) 
View(freq_table)                          

## PRACTICE: try this command without the transform function and inspect its class()
## Remember to also delete the set of parentheses corresponding to
## that function

#4 lastly, we create a data frame for our frequency distribution table by adding:
## (1) the relative frequency using the prop.table function  and (2) the cumulative frequency using ## the cumsum function (search the help to learn what exactly each of  these functions do)

groupFrequency2<-transform(freq_table2,Rel_freq=prop.table(Freq),Cum_Freq=cumsum(Freq))

View(groupFrequency)

STEP 3

Plot a histogram

To plot a histogram we use the function hist. You can learn what the function does by typing hist into the search box in the Help tab oo by typing hist? in the console. Below we will use the function to plot a histogram using the default settings of the function and then, we will plot another two specifying the class intervals we made above for both of our frequency tables.

################ PLOT A HISTOGRAM ###########
# we create an object to save our histogram. Here we use hist1
hist1<-hist(hhsize$size_cm, 
            xlab= "cm",                    # provide a label for the x axis
            main= "Hedgehog size in cm",   # provide a title for the plot
            col="green")                   # specify the colour we want the bins to have

# You have a pdf file called R color cheat sheet with the names of all colors and hues

Copy and paste the histogram into your Word Answer file.

From the plot you can see that the function hist used 7 class intervals of width 5 cm from 0 to 35. This is because the default value for the parameter breaks is set to symmetrical intervals. However, we can also specify the breaks we want. Let us do this and use the breaks we calculated for our grouped frequency tables.

################ PLOT A HISTOGRAM  SPECIFYING THE BREAKS ###########

# we create an object to save our histogram. Here we use hist2 
hist2<-hist(hhsize$size_cm, 
            breaks = binNum,            # specify which breaks to use (same as our freq_table)
            xlab= "cm",                    # provide a label for the x axis
            main= "Hedgehog size in cm",   # provide a title for the plot
            col="blue")

# Do the same for the second class intervals width of 9.
# we create an object to save our histogram. Here we use hist3 
hist3<-hist(hhsize$size_cm, 
            breaks = binNum2,            # specify which breaks to use (same as our freq_table)
            xlab= "cm",                    # provide a label for the x axis
            main= "Hedgehog size in cm",   # provide a title for the plot
            col="red")

Copy and paste both histograms into your Word Answer file.

Question 3: How would you describe the shape of the distribution of the size of hedgehogs from the first histogram?

Question 3.1: How did the shape of the distribution of the size of hedgehogs changed when increasing the bin width?

If we inspect the histogram object we just created using the class intervals of our frequency table, we can see that the function hist outputs a list that has stored: (1) a vector named breaks for the bins of the histogram (2) a vector named counts with the simple frequency of values per bin (3) a vector named density with the density within each bin (4) a vector named mids with the mid points of the class intervals or bins (5) a character string named xname with the name of the variable (6) the attributes and class of the object

We can use what we learned about slicing lists in “Practical 0” to extract the density and add it to our groupedFrequency instead of estimating the densities for each bin ourselves

################ GET THE VALUES OF DENSITY FOR EACH BIN  ###########

# slice the object hist2 as if it were a list to extract the values of density
density<-hist2$density

# add these values of density as a column or variable in our dat frame or grouped frequency
 groupFrequency<-cbind.data.frame(groupFrequency,density)

 # inspect to corroborate it worked correctly
 View(groupFrequency)
 
 # save or "write" the frequency table.
 write.csv(groupFrequency,file = "hedgehogSize_FreqTable.csv")

Check your folder to verify the file was saved. Open the file in Excel

STEP 4

Calculate the measures of central tendency and dispersion

R has a built in function that provide us with the descriptive statistics we need to summarise the variables that are within a dataframe or as a vector. If we use the function summary, R will print in the console the most important statistics to summarise, and have an idea of the distribution of each of the variables in a dataset. Functions for each measure of location and spread are also available in R base

################ GET THE SUMMARY STATISTICS  ###########

summary(hhsize)

# mean
mean(hhsize$size_cm)

# variance
var(hhsize$size_cm)

# standard deviation of the sample mean
sd(hhsize$size_cm)

# quantiles
quantile(hhsize$size_cm)

Copy and paste these values in your Word Answer file and arrange them in a table.

Question 5: What is the value of the inter-quartile range for the size of hedgehogs?

Question 5.1: What do the mean and median tell you about the distribution of the variable size?

We can now use a boxplot to illustrate how the data is distributed

boxplot(hhsize$size_cm,                # specify the variable we want to plot
        main = "size of hedgehogs",    # main title
        ylab = "size in cm",           # label of y axis
        col =  "grey")                 # colour we want the box to be filled with

You can play with many different colours. In the pdf file named Cheat-Sheet_Rcolors.pdf within the Practical_1 folder you will find a list of the different colours you can use in R.

STEP 5

Report on your summary statistics

Every time we are reporting on our results, there is a minimum information that should be provided for the variable(s) of interest. Beside a table containing a summary of the measures of location and spread, we need to provide a description in narrative form:

The size of hedgehogs for the 2021 survey in Easthampton council ranged between 2.5cm and 33.7cm with an average of 9.18cm \(\pm\) 6.11cm (mean \(\pm\) SD). The majority (55.5%) of measured hedgehogs were in between 15cm and 25cm (reference a boxplot or histogram)
